Flight log has officially been activated! I have 2.3 hours of flight records now ^_^
#TeaganAir
If you ask me to describe what it's like to fly a small airplane, I would say it's like driving a combination of a motorcycle/ATV and a boat at 4000 feet in the air.
On the ground, things are constantly changing. The ground has a certain level of instability, so it's like driving a motorcycle/ATV.
Another thing you might not know is that when flying on the ground, you use your feet to control the direction, not the steering wheel. You use the rudder pedals and brakes. It's not like driving a car.
When flying in the air, you will feel turbulence and oscillation, feeling like you're sailing on water. You can control the plane, but sometimes the air currents will make you dizzy, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like sailors adapt to navigation.
There's also a random little tidbit about this:
Flying is physically demanding. Today my back and legs are so sore, feeling like I just went to the gym and worked out.
This is not as simple as just driving out for a Sunday cruise. For a beginner like me, it feels more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, have a happy Saturday. Welcome to 4000 feet in the air.
Tomorrow I will fly again, and we will practice gliding and slow flying.
Today's weather was not very stable, but it was super fun. We practiced slow flying and gliding. Our ground speed dropped to 16 miles/hour, and our air speed was still 65 miles/hour.
Today the weather was clear, and although the air was a bit misty at high altitude, the visibility was still great.
FlightAware data track.
This is similar to going to the gym for exercise. I'm so exhausted today that I slept for two whole hours (just woke up). And my whole body aches, especially my legs. I used the right rudder many times today.
